1
00:00:40,120 --> 00:00:44,921
In 1945, America's greatest
generation came back from war.

2
00:00:47,040 --> 00:00:49,646
The flags of freedom fly
over Europe.

3
00:00:51,320 --> 00:00:52,960
Nazi Germany had been defeated...

4
00:00:53,000 --> 00:00:57,085
and three months later, Imperial
Japan surrendered, as well.

5
00:00:57,280 --> 00:00:59,647
And there's jubilation around
this Earth.

6
00:00:59,800 --> 00:01:01,156
Men returned home.

7
00:01:01,256 --> 00:01:04,428
Among them, some of baseball's
most beloved names.

8
00:01:04,563 --> 00:01:07,449
Musial... DiMaggio... Williams.

9
00:01:07,600 --> 00:01:10,004
Life in the United States
could return to normal.

10
00:01:10,104 --> 00:01:11,752
I don't know what's the guy's
name on first base!

11
00:01:11,852 --> 00:01:13,217
What's on second?
Who's on second?

12
00:01:13,317 --> 00:01:14,666
Who's on first?
I don't know.

13
00:01:14,766 --> 00:01:15,699
Third base.

14
00:01:15,799 --> 00:01:19,088
And baseball was proof positive
that democracy was real.

15
00:01:19,840 --> 00:01:22,650
A baseball box score, after all,
is a democratic thing.

16
00:01:22,800 --> 00:01:25,531
It doesn't say how big you are,
or what religion you follow.

17
00:01:25,680 --> 00:01:28,365
It does not know how you voted,
or the color of your skin.

18
00:01:28,560 --> 00:01:31,001
It simply states what kind of
ballplayer you were...

19
00:01:31,101 --> 00:01:32,631
on any particular day.

20
00:01:32,766 --> 00:01:33,924
And he did it.
It's a home run.

21
00:01:34,080 --> 00:01:35,923
They knew he'd do it.

22
00:01:36,080 --> 00:01:39,323
African Americans had served
their country gallantly.

23
00:01:39,480 --> 00:01:41,434
But they returned home from
fighting the war...

24
00:01:41,534 --> 00:01:42,699
to free the world from tyranny...

25
00:01:42,799 --> 00:01:45,705
only to find racism, segregation
and Jim Crow law...

26
00:01:45,805 --> 00:01:46,639
still waiting at home.

27
00:01:46,774 --> 00:01:49,047
Segregation was the law and
custom of the land...

28
00:01:49,200 --> 00:01:52,443
and no group was more scrupulous
in its observance of custom...

29
00:01:52,600 --> 00:01:54,170
than organized baseball.

30
00:01:54,320 --> 00:01:55,860
There was a long road ahead.

31
00:01:59,520 --> 00:02:01,887
If African Americans dreamed of
playing baseball...

32
00:02:02,040 --> 00:02:03,690
it was not for the New York
Yankees...

33
00:02:03,840 --> 00:02:05,658
but for teams like the Kansas
City Monarchs...

34
00:02:05,758 --> 00:02:08,591
of the Negro Leagues, where the
barnstorming style of play...

35
00:02:08,691 --> 00:02:10,736
stood in contrast to the Majors.

36
00:02:11,440 --> 00:02:14,330
In 1946, there were sixteen
Major League baseball teams...

37
00:02:14,480 --> 00:02:17,882
with a total of 400 players
on their rosters.

38
00:02:18,040 --> 00:02:20,691
Every one of the 400 players
were white.

39
00:02:20,840 --> 00:02:26,529
But when opening day came in 1947,
that number dropped to 399...

40
00:02:26,680 --> 00:02:28,603
and one man stood apart.

41
00:02:48,240 --> 00:02:52,529
Gentlemen, I have a plan.

42
00:02:53,880 --> 00:02:56,611
Plan's good, Mr. Rickey.
You always have one.

43
00:02:56,760 --> 00:02:59,445
My wife says I'm too old.

44
00:03:01,360 --> 00:03:04,045
That my health's not up to it.

45
00:03:05,560 --> 00:03:09,121
My son says, uh, everybody in...

46
00:03:10,080 --> 00:03:14,290
everybody in baseball is gonna
be against me.

47
00:03:16,520 --> 00:03:18,522
But I'm gonna do it.

48
00:03:19,440 --> 00:03:21,602
Do what, Mr. Rickey?

49
00:03:22,440 --> 00:03:25,808
I'm gonna bring a Negro
ballplayer...

50
00:03:26,800 --> 00:03:29,451
to the Brooklyn Dodgers.

51
00:03:37,440 --> 00:03:40,125
With all due respect, sir,
have you lost your mind?

52
00:03:41,880 --> 00:03:44,406
Think... think about...

53
00:03:45,960 --> 00:03:47,086
think about the abuse...

54
00:03:47,240 --> 00:03:49,527
that you are gonna take from
the newspapers...

55
00:03:49,680 --> 00:03:52,524
let alone how this is gonna
play out in Flatbush!

56
00:03:53,080 --> 00:03:54,809
Please, Mr. Rickey.

57
00:03:55,040 --> 00:03:56,963
Sit down, Harold.

58
00:04:04,920 --> 00:04:07,491
No law against it, Clyde.

59
00:04:08,440 --> 00:04:09,965
No.

60
00:04:10,560 --> 00:04:12,801
No, but there's a code.

61
00:04:13,920 --> 00:04:15,414
You break a law and get away
with it...

62
00:04:15,573 --> 00:04:17,576
some people think you're smart.

63
00:04:19,160 --> 00:04:21,401
You break an unwritten law...

64
00:04:22,680 --> 00:04:25,001
you'll be an outcast.

65
00:04:25,200 --> 00:04:26,201
Mm-hm.

66
00:04:27,600 --> 00:04:29,364
So be it.

67
00:04:30,600 --> 00:04:34,446
New York's full of Negro
baseball fans.

68
00:04:36,160 --> 00:04:41,121
Dollars aren't black and white,
they're green.

69
00:04:41,280 --> 00:04:43,726
Every dollar's green.

70
00:04:45,200 --> 00:04:47,248
I don't know who he is...

71
00:04:48,040 --> 00:04:49,883
or where he is...

72
00:04:51,720 --> 00:04:53,643
but he's coming.

73
00:04:57,400 --> 00:04:58,811
Hey, runner!

74
00:04:58,960 --> 00:05:02,169
Where'd you learn to move like
that? At a dime-a-dance night?

75
00:05:02,360 --> 00:05:03,850
Stand still!

76
00:05:04,000 --> 00:05:05,411
There you are!

77
00:05:06,880 --> 00:05:07,881
Ball!

78
00:05:09,720 --> 00:05:11,484
Safe!

79
00:05:12,240 --> 00:05:13,526
Catcher!

80
00:05:13,680 --> 00:05:15,569
When you gonna start throwing
for real?

81
00:05:15,720 --> 00:05:17,006
You talking to me?

82
00:05:17,160 --> 00:05:19,162
You got a rag arm, catcher.

83
00:05:19,560 --> 00:05:22,530
Steal home. You'll find out
what kind of arm I got.

84
00:05:22,680 --> 00:05:24,444
Okay.

85
00:05:24,640 --> 00:05:25,766
I'm coming.

86
00:05:27,080 --> 00:05:28,764
Where's your shortstop from?

87
00:05:28,920 --> 00:05:30,081
California.

88
00:05:30,240 --> 00:05:32,402
Sure got a mouth on him.

89
00:05:42,360 --> 00:05:43,407
Safe!

90
00:05:56,640 --> 00:05:59,769
Discussions concerning Japan's
offer of surrender.

91
00:05:59,960 --> 00:06:02,406
Washington, London, Moscow,
and Chungking...

92
00:06:02,560 --> 00:06:04,608
now framing their decision.

93
00:06:04,800 --> 00:06:07,480
When this decision will be
communicated to Tokyo...

94
00:06:07,580 --> 00:06:08,393
via the government's...

95
00:06:08,528 --> 00:06:10,647
Fill her up?
Yes, sir.

96
00:06:13,720 --> 00:06:16,451
You boys heading out...
Uh, Chicago.

97
00:06:16,680 --> 00:06:18,409
Chicago, huh?
Heh.

98
00:06:19,040 --> 00:06:22,283
You boys get around.
Yeah, we sure do.

99
00:06:24,400 --> 00:06:27,563
Hey. Hey, you, where you going?
To the toilet.

100
